		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2009"></a><br><code>sle2009/paper19</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Declarative Scripting in Haskell</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/TimBauer.html">Tim Bauer</a>, <a href="../profile/MartinErwig.html">Martin Erwig</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_21">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_21</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> It presents a scripting language approach built in/with Haskell, i.e., a DSL for scripting.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The scripting approach relies on integration/embedding into the Haskell host language and its ecosystem.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL">T3D: GPLs</span></a><ul><li> Haskell, as a general-purpose language, serves as the substrate for the declarative scripting design.
</li></ul></li></ul>
